Dear All,
  Thanks for agreeing to be part of this initiative. Thanks to Lars
Eggert for initiating this and to Jon Crowcroft for naming the group
which seems to have relevance to Gaia hypothesis.

The idea is to clearly understand and scope out what are the
challenges in universal service provisioning and where and how we
could shape the future Internet architectures to support wider access.
To do that we need a real mix of expertise to shape this agenda - so
we need input from diverse disciplines (not only tech, but also
economics/social/policy/regulatory/hci etc).

We currently have a diverse set of experts with backgrounds and
experience here in the mailing list: ranging from pioneers who have
deep rooted experience doing in-the-wild deployments in emerging
regions as well as in developed countries, wireless, satellite,
white-space, network architectures, measurements, CDNs, SDN, ICN, DTN,
pricing/incentives, standardization. We are currently aiming to get
more people across the other disciplines as well as well as several
other organisations whom we have contacted (A4AI, CTO, ResearchICT
Africa etc). We need more participation from organisations from
emerging regions and it will be great if you could pass this info if
you have any contacts.

This is a great and unique opportunity for all of us to come together
under one umbrella to push standards efforts that could potentially
change the Internet landscape to be more inclusive. There have been
several past and present work in this space, some of which have
succeeded into self sustainable deployments and some that have failed
- and it will be great to get input on the challenges and experiences.
Encouragingly, the Internet technological landscape has also changed
with diverse set of technologies and clean slate Internet
architectures that if carefully thought and integrated together could
solve some of the challenges that were impossible to overcome
previously.

Lars - would you like to add any thoughts as well as possible next steps?

Regards
Arjuna

