Subject: Re: [gaia] Welcome to GAIA

Thanks Lars.

Just to introduce myself as well..

I am a Senior Researcher at the Computer Laboratory where I lead the
Lowest Cost Denominator Networking initiative
(http://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/~as2330/lcd/) with Jon Crowcroft. As Lars
pointed out, this is a fundamental social problem and the only way I
could contribute is through the knowledge I have gained over the years
- thats in networking.

Our work at Cambridge (through several collaborations) currently
focusses on

(1)  Efficiently utilise unused capacity in networks facilitating the
creation of new economic models through multi-stakeholder (who have
socio-environmental objectives rather than purely economic) subsidised
access

(2) Exploring the role of technologies like ICN/DTN and how we could
bring them together under one single abstraction and what are the
benefits such an abstraction could bring - what we are trying to do is
to bridge the gap between those who have and dont have - which in turn
means we probably have an "opportunity" to explore new promising
existing concepts/tech which potentially could improve access but also
reduce the cost of access.
The last 5-10 years of active research in these areas have shown some
promising results (DTN's timeshifting of content + additional
reliability in energy constrained unreliable links; ICN's ability to do
edge caching + localised access + reduce wastage etc)..

(3) Exploring new architectures that facilitate better sharing of access
infrastructures (www.publicaccesswifi.org) thereby reducing CAPEX as
well as architectures that allow multi-stakeholder involvement thereby
reducing OPEX. We are exploring the role of SDN + Scavenger access here.

My involvement will be to bootstrap this group and I am hoping the more
experienced folks run the show :)..

Hoping to hear from others too..

Regards
Arjuna

