Dear all,

Continuing the round here:
My name's Dirk Trossen and I'm a Principal Scientist at InterDigital UK, the newly established European presence of InterDigital Inc. I've come to discuss with Arjuna about architectural problems (and possible
solutions) for universal access during my time at Cambridge University (which ended in April 2013).

In my new role, I have a continued interest in architectural issues that create obstacles to widespread Internet access availability, utilizing advances in areas such as edge caching, ICN, and new backhaul technologies to overcome such obstacles in order to push the Internet to those who don't have proper access (and simply can't afford due to unsustainable economic foundations of how the Internet would be provided to them). 

I'm very excited about the IETF/IRTF having established a forum to discuss these issues. I hope that our initial circle will find extension from those who can provide us with insights into the needs of those who seek Internet access and the obstacles that hinder it. It seems obvious to me that we have a lot to share and a lot to learn.

Best,

Dirk 

