Our work at Cambridge (through several collaborations) currently focusses o=
n

(1)  Efficiently utilise unused capacity in networks facilitating the creat=
ion of new economic models through multi-stakeholder (who have socio-enviro=
nmental objectives rather than purely economic) subsidised access

(2) Exploring the role of technologies like ICN/DTN and how we could bring =
them together under one single abstraction and what are the benefits such a=
n abstraction could bring - what we are trying to do is to bridge the gap b=
etween those who have and dont have - which in turn means we probably have =
an &quot;opportunity&quot; to explore new promising existing concepts/tech =
which potentially could improve access but also reduce the cost of access.
The last 5-10 years of active research in these areas have shown some promi=
sing results (DTN&#39;s timeshifting of content + additional reliability in=
 energy constrained unreliable links; ICN&#39;s ability to do edge caching =
+ localised access + reduce wastage etc)..

(3) Exploring new architectures that facilitate better sharing of access in=
frastructures (<a href=3D"http://www.publicaccesswifi.org" target=3D"_blank=
">www.publicaccesswifi.org</a>) thereby reducing CAPEX as well as architect=
ures that allow multi-stakeholder involvement thereby reducing OPEX. We are=
 exploring the role of SDN + Scavenger access here.

My involvement will be to bootstrap this group and I am hoping the more exp=
erienced folks run the show :)..

Hoping to hear from others too..

