Hi,

Pleased to meet you all. I'm Jay Chen a Computer Science professor at 
NYU in Abu Dhabi, also a member of CTED.

I work in a similar research space as Lakshmi. My dissertation work was 
focused on information access for developing regions. I explored 
possible solutions across different technologies, networking layers, 
application areas, and contexts. More info about me specifically may be 
found: http://cs.nyu.edu/~jchen/ <http://cs.nyu.edu/%7Ejchen/>

I'm looking forward to this discussion.

Thanks,
Jay


On 12/19/2013 9:44 AM, Lakshminarayanan Subramanian wrote:
> Looks like my earlier introduction email (from gmail) did not make it to
> the mailing list. Resending it.
>
> Hi, I am Lakshmi Subramanian.
>
> I know a few of you in the mailing list. For those whom I dont know,
> here's a quick bio: I am a professor at NYU and co-lead the Center for
> Technology and Economic Development (CTED) where we work on different
> technological solutions for global developmental problems. We work in
> different areas including core technical problems such as connectivity,
> information access, mobile
> systems, off-grid solar and applied areas such as education, food and health.
>
> With respect to this audience, relevant projects include:
> a) long-distance WiFi (joint work with the Berkeley TIER group with Eric,
> Kevin, Yahel and others).
> b) Contextual Information Portals (offline Web access modules powered by
> context-specific prefetching crawlers which we have used for delivering
> educational content in schools in India, Kenya, Ghana)
> c) Low-bandwidth transport and Web caching architectures for low-bandwidth
> networks
> d) mobile systems and services that work in extreme network conditions
> (SMS based search, SMS powered Apps, mobile apps for health and
> agriculture)
> e) off-grid solar powered computing (solar-powered cell towers, clusters
> etc.)
> Currently, we are doing some work on enhancing mobile web and rural
> cellular network architectures.
>
> I would also like to point the folks in this mailing list to two specific
> conferences:
> 1. ACM Symposium on Computing for Development (DEV):  http://acmdev.org
> 2. Information and Communication Technologies for Development (ICTD):
> http://ictd2013.org
>
> DEV and ICTD have emerged as the premier conferences on problems relating
> to computing and communication solutions for development. DEV is much more
> CS-focused on new technological solutions and ICTD is much more
> interdisciplinary (with participation from Econ, Social Sciences) with a
> focus on evaluating the impact of technology. There have 4 ACM DEV
> conferences so far and 5-6 ICTD conferences so far. DEV has 100-150 CS
> people attending every year and ICTD attracts a broader array of 450-500
> people (which includes the 100-150 CS people in DEV). Typically, these two
> conferences have been co-located. The last one happened 1-2 weeks before
> in South Africa.
>
> cheers
> lakshmi
>
